output.crosstab_text:
For level 8 graduates of Allied health, five years after graduation, the industry with the highest proportion of graduates is the same for both female and male graduates (Education). The median earnings for females in this industry were £38,700 and for males were £43,100.

The biggest difference in proportions is seen in Education where the proportion of female graduates is 12.4 percentage points higher than the proportion of male graduates. The biggest difference in median earnings is seen in Human health and social work activities where the median earnings of male graduates were £49,900 higher than the median earnings of female graduates. The group with the highest earnings was Male graduates who worked in the Human health and social work activities industry (median earnings of £86,500). 77.8% of female graduates are concentrated in the top 2 industries (either Education or Human health and social work activities), whereas for male graduates this is 64.3%.
